The paper deals with the problem of leader election in population protocols, which is a subfield of Distributed Computing (cs.DC). The paper also discusses the space complexity of the protocol, which falls under the category of Information Theory (cs.IT). The use of phase clocks for synchronisation and coordination is a common technique in Distributed Computing, which could place the paper under the sub-category of Systems and Control (cs.SY). The paper also proposes a new protocol, which involves pairwise interactions between agents, making it relevant to the sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper uses formal argumentation to prove the correctness and efficiency of the proposed protocol, which could place it under the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG).
